5.  Java Message Service (JMS) 
    It is a Java API for sending messages between systems asynchronously.
      👉 Instead of direct communication: Service A → Service B (tight coupling ❌)
      👉 Use messaging: Service A → Message Queue → Service B (loose coupling ✅)

  What does “Asynchronous” mean? Sender does NOT wait for receiver
    Synchronous (REST style) -Service A → Service B → Response (wait)
        ❌ Blocking
        ❌ Slower under load
    Asynchronous (JMS) - Service A → Queue → (continues immediately)
                        ↓
                     Service B processes later
    
        ✔ Non-blocking
        ✔ Faster
        ✔ Decoupled
    jmsTemplate.convertAndSend("orderQueue", order);
    System.out.println("Order sent"); // runs immediately👉 No waiting for consumer

  Why JMS?
        Decouples systems
        Enables async processing
        Improves scalability
        Handles high load
 
  JMS Architecture
    Producer → Message Broker → Consumer
    🔹 1. Producer -Sends message
    🔹 2. Consumer - Receives message
    🔹 3. Message - Data being sent
    🔹 4. Destination -Where message goes Queue/Topic
    🔹 5. Message Broker -  Manages messages like ActiveMQ/RabbitMQ

   Message Types:
      🔹 TextMessage -"Hello World"
      🔹 ObjectMessage-Serializable object
      🔹 MapMessage - Key-value pairs
      🔹 BytesMessage -Binary data
  
  Messaging Models
      🔹 1. Queue (Point-to-Point) :Producer → Queue → ONE Consumer   
                          ✔ One consumer gets message
                          ✔ Load balancing
      🔹 2. Topic (Publish-Subscribe) : Producer → Topic → MANY Consumers
                          ✔ All subscribers receive message
  JMS with Spring:
    In the Spring Framework, JMS is simplified using: JmsTemplate  Like JdbcTemplate (for DB)
      🔹 Sending Message
            @Autowired
            private JmsTemplate jmsTemplate;
      
            jmsTemplate.convertAndSend("queue", "Hello JMS");
      🔹 Receiving Message
            @JmsListener(destination = "queue")
            public void receive(String message) {
                System.out.println(message);
            }
      Internal Working: convertAndSend → MessageConverter → Broker → Listener → Method execution
      Message ConversionL Spring converts Java object ↔ JMS message
            jmsTemplate.convertAndSend("queue", user);  ✔ Automatically serialized

    Transactions in JMS👉 Ensure message reliability
        @Transactional
        public void send() {
            jmsTemplate.convertAndSend("queue", "msg");
        }
        ✔ If transaction fails → message not sent
    
    Handling Timeouts in JMS
      Timeouts can happen when: Waiting for message, Broker delay and Consumer slow
      🔹 A. Receive Timeout - jmsTemplate.setReceiveTimeout(5000); // 5 seconds 👉 If no message → returns null
      🔹 B. Request-Reply Timeout - If using request-response pattern: jmsTemplate.setReceiveTimeout(3000);
      🔹 C. Connection Timeout - Configured in broker/client: ActiveMQ connection URL/ ConnectionFactory config
      Best Practices :Set proper timeout values, Avoid infinite waits and  Use retry mechanism

    What if Queue / Broker is NOT UP?
    ❌ Problem :App → JMS → Broker DOWN → Exception
     Handling Strategies
        ✔ 1. Retry Mechanism
              try {
                  jmsTemplate.convertAndSend("queue", msg);
              } catch (Exception e) {
                  // retry logic
              }
        Use: RetryTemplate (Spring),  Custom retry loop
        ✔ 2. Circuit Breaker (Advanced) 👉 Stop sending temporarily Tools: Resilience4j
        ✔ 3. Message Persistence👉 If broker is up but consumer down: ✔ Messages stored in broker ✔ Delivered later 
        ✔ 4. Failover Configuration: For brokers like ActiveMQ: failover:(tcp://host1:61616,tcp://host2:61616) ✔ Switches to backup broker
        ✔ 5. Dead Letter Queue (DLQ): 👉 Failed messages go here : queue → failure → DLQ ✔ Prevents data loss    
        ✔ 6. Logging & Alerting ✔ Monitor broker health ✔ Send alerts
    
     Acknowledgement Modes👉 Defines when message is considered successfully consumed
      🔹 1. AUTO_ACKNOWLEDGE- Session.AUTO_ACKNOWLEDGE 
                  ✔ Automatically acknowledged after processing
                  Receive → Process → Auto ACK
                  ⚠️ Risk If failure during processing → message lost
      🔹 2. CLIENT_ACKNOWLEDGE - Session.CLIENT_ACKNOWLEDGE
                  ✔ Manual acknowledgment
                  message.acknowledge();
                  Receive → Process → ACK manually
                  ✔ Advantage- Better control, Retry possible
      🔹 3. DUPS_OK_ACKNOWLEDGE -Session.DUPS_OK_ACKNOWLEDGE
                  ✔ Lazy acknowledgment
                  May deliver duplicates
                  Faster performance
                  ⚠️ Requirement👉 Consumer must handle duplicates
      🔹 4. TRANSACTED SESSION 
                  session.commit();
                  session.rollback();
                  Receive →Process →Commit → ACK
                  Rollback → message redelivered
                  ✔ Best for reliability
                  Ensures no data loss
                  Supports rollback
  Delivery Modes:
  🔹 Persistent - ✔ Saved to disk✔ Reliable
  🔹 Non-Persistent -✔ Faster ❌ Risk of loss
  
